If you mean “What other spatial perspectives naturally transition into mindsets or mental models?”, there are a lot. Maps are powerful because they’re really externalized ways of thinking.

Here are a few:

Spatial model	Mental model it evokes
South-up map	Question assumptions. “Up” is arbitrary.
Polar projection	Think from the center outward rather than from the edges inward.
Globe	Continuous systems; there are no true edges.
Mercator projection	Utility over truth. Great for navigation, poor for comparing sizes.
Equal-area projection	Fairness over familiarity. Preserve proportions even if shapes distort.
Gnomonic projection	The shortest path isn’t always obvious; great-circle thinking.
Interrupted projections (Goode Homolosine)	Sometimes separating pieces reveals patterns hidden by forcing everything into one frame.
Dymaxion map (Buckminster Fuller)	Remove arbitrary geopolitical orientation and see humanity as one connected island.
Antipode map	Every place has an opposite. Perspective is relational.
Topographic map	Success isn’t just distance—it’s elevation and terrain.
Subway map	Preserve relationships, ignore physical accuracy. Useful abstraction.
Heat map	Attention should follow intensity, not geography.
Network graph	Connections matter more than location.
Flow map	Think in movement rather than objects. Rivers, trade, information, migration.
Time-zone map	Simultaneous realities can coexist. “Now” depends on where you stand.

You can go even broader.

Instead of asking “Where is it?”, different maps ask different questions:

* Topological → What is connected?
* Metric → How far apart?
* Hierarchical → Who influences whom?
* Temporal → When does change happen?
* Probabilistic → Where is it likely to be?
* Narrative → How do people experience this place?
* Semantic → What does this mean?
* Causal → What causes what?

One pattern I find especially useful is this progression:

Maps → Perspectives → Mental Models → Decisions → Actions

Changing the map often changes the decisions, even when the underlying territory stays exactly the same. That’s why flipping the Earth south-up can feel surprisingly profound: the planet hasn’t changed—only the frame through which you’re interpreting it.